<br>
Several years ago, I returned home from a trip just when <br>
<br>
a storm hit, with crashing thunder and severe lightning. As I came <br>
<br>
into my bedroom about 2a.m., I found my two children in bed with my <br>
<br>
wife, Karey, apparently scared by the loud storm. I resigned <br>
<br>
myself to sleep in the guest bedroom that night. The next day, I <br>
<br>
talked to the children, and explained that it was O.K. to sleep with <br>
<br>
Mommy when the storm was bad, but when I was expected home, please <br>
<br>
don't sleep with Mommy that night. They said OK. <br>
<br>
After my next trip several weeks later, Karey and the children picked <br>
me up in the airport terminal at the appointed time. Since the plane <br>
<br>
was late, everyone had come into the terminal to wait for my plane's <br>
arrival along with hundreds of other folks waiting for their arriving <br>
<br>
passengers. As I entered the waiting area, my 5 year old son saw me, and began <br>
<br>
shouting, "Hi, Daddy! I've got some good news!" As I waved back, I <br>
<br>
said loudly, "What's the good news, son?" He replied very loudly, <br>
<br>
"Nobody slept with Mommy while you were away this time!" <br>
<br>
Everyone in the terminal looked at me, then my wife, who'd turned 59 <br>
<br>
shades of red in the span of 10 seconds. I laughed so hard I ached. <br>
<br>
 <br>
  An acquaintance of mine who is a physician told this story about her <br>
then 4yr old daughter. On the way to preschool, the doctor had <br>
left her stethoscope on the car seat, and her little girl picked it <br>
up and began playing with it. 'Be still, my heart,' thought my friend, <br>
my daughter wants to follow in my footsteps!' Then the child spoke to <br>
the instrument: "Welcome to McDonald's. May I take your order?" <br>
